{{Infobox album | name = A Beautiful Mind | type = film | artist = [[James Horner]] | cover = A Beautiful Mind cd.jpg | alt = | released = {{start date|2001|12|11}} | recorded = 2001 | venue = | studio = | genre = Classical, jazz, stage & screen | length = | label = [[Decca Records|Decca]] <small>440 016 191-2</small> | producer = James Horner, Simon Rhodes | prev_title = [[Enemy at the Gates]] | prev_year = 2001 | next_title = [[Iris (2001 film)|Iris]] | next_year = 2001 }}
'''''A Beautiful Mind''''' is the original [[soundtrack album]], on the Decca Records label, of the 2001 film ''[[A Beautiful Mind (film)|A Beautiful Mind]]'' starring [[Russell Crowe]], [[Jennifer Connelly]] (who won the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress for her role as "Alicia Nash"), [[Christopher Plummer]] and [[Paul Bettany]]. The original [[Film score|score]] and [[song]]s were composed and conducted by [[James Horner]].
The album garnered nominations for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]]. Music critics felt that the musical score fit the film well, but believed it to be similar to several of Horner's previous films.
==Development== Composer [[James Horner]] was a frequent collaborator with [[Ron Howard]], the director of ''A Beautiful Mind''. Horner desired to feature vocals reminiscent of being midway between a girl and woman,<ref name=NPR>{{Cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-51458075.html |title=Analysis: Film scores for "A Beautiful Mind" and "A.I.: Artificial Intelligence" |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |first=Lynn|last=Neary |date=March 10, 2002 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}} {{Subscription needed}}</ref> and wrote the score specifically for 15-year-old [[Welsh people|Welsh]] singer [[Charlotte Church]]. In an interview, she stated that it was "one of the most haunting and beautiful [things] I have ever performed."<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79349220.html |title=Charlotte Has an Oscar in Her Beautiful Mind |work=[[The Mail on Sunday]] |first=Katie|last=Nicholl|date=October 21, 2001 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}} {{Subscription needed}}</ref> To convey "the beauty of mathematics," Horner decided to use the idea of a [[kaleidoscope]], as its "patterns are always changing, and things move very quickly, but in moving so quickly, they create other patterns that move very slowly underneath."<ref name=DailyVariety/> He added that these changing patterns were conveyed with the piano and Church's voice.<ref name=DailyVariety>{{Cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-83030727.html |title=Magic lies in the methods: This year's crop of possible contenders use mix of traditional and unusual scoring elements |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] |first=Jon |last=Burlingame |date=January 23, 2002 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}} {{Subscription needed}}</ref>
==Release and reception== {{Album ratings |rev1 = [[Filmtracks.com]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/beautiful_mind.html |publisher=[[Filmtracks.com]] |title=A Beautiful Mind (James Horner) |first=Christian |last=Clemmensen |date=December 7, 2001 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> |rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}} |rev2 = [[Soundtrack.net]]<ref name=Soundtrackreview>{{Cite news|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/soundtracks/database/?id=3073 |title=Review |publisher=[[Soundtrack.net]] |first=Dan |last=Goldwasser |date=December 1, 2001 |accessdate=January 12, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231064843/http://www.soundtrack.net/soundtracks/database/?id=3073 |archivedate=December 31, 2006 |df= }}</ref> |rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}} }} Writing for ''Empire'' magazine, Danny Graydon gave the soundtrack four out of five stars. He thought the score contained elements of Horner's previous films ''[[Sneakers (1992 film)|Sneakers]]'' (1992) and ''[[Bicentennial Man (film)|Bicentennial Man]]'' (1999), but said "if you can forgive that, this is a clever, masterful and romantic score that captures a brilliant mind in conflict."<ref name=EmpireReview>{{Cite news |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=7787 |title=Empire's A Beautiful Mind Soundtrack Review |work=Empire |first=Danny |last=Graydon |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> In the tracks "Creating Government Dynamics" and "Cracking The Russian Codes", Graydon opined that Church's "poignant vocals mix well with the frenetic piano and strings to represent Nash’s brilliance," and wished that her voice had been used more in the film.<ref name=EmpireReview/>
Dan Goldwasser of [[Soundtrack.net]] also found similarities to the score in ''Bicentennial Man'', but thought Horner's work fit the film regardless, explaining "it effectively underscores the drama and romance, and even provides a few bits of tension for the action scene."<ref name=Soundtrackreview/> Goldwasser concluded that "while it all works well in the film, there is enough about this score that just seemed to {{sic}} 'familiar' to make it stand out.<ref name=Soundtrackreview/> Contributing to [[National Public Radio]], Andy Trudeau believed Church's particular voice adds a "human element. It's the sound that, I think, gives a sense of--the center of this character, if you will. I think it's the soul. And it's trying to be normal in a way, and underneath it it's trying to be crazy."<ref name=NPR/>
Horner's score garnered nominations for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-321700.html |title=Harrison Ford To Be Honored At Golden Globes |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 20, 2002 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}} {{Subscription needed}}</ref> and the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4616983.html |title=And the Nominees Are... |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=December 21, 2001 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}} {{Subscription needed}}</ref> It lost the Golden Globe to the film ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' and the Oscar to ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]''.
==Track listing== Adapted from:<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-beautiful-mind-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000227666 |title=A Beautiful Mind [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack] |work=Allmusic |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> {| class="tracklist" |- !No. !! Title |- | 1 || "A Kaleidoscope of Mathematics" |- | 2 || "Playing a Game of 'Go!'" |- | 3 || "Looking for the Next Great Idea" |- | 4 || "Creating 'Governing Dynamics'" |- | 5 || "Cracking the Russian Codes" |- | 6 || "Nash Descends into Parcher's World" |- | 7 || "First Drop-Off, First Kiss" |- | 8 || "The Car Chase" |- | 9 || "Alicia Discovers Nash's Dark World" |- | 10 || "Real or Imagined?" |- | 11 || "Of One Heart, of One Mind" |- | 12 || "Saying Goodbye to Those You So Love" |- | 13 || "Teaching Mathematics Again" |- | 14 || "The Prize of One's Life... The Prize of One's Mind" |- | 15 || "All Love Can Be" <small>([[Charlotte Church]])</small> |- | 16 || "Closing Credits" |- |}
