{{italic title}} [[Image:'Dying Slave' Michelangelo JBU001.jpg|thumb|''Dying Slave'']] The '''''Dying Slave''''' is a sculpture by the [[Italian Renaissance]] artist [[Michelangelo]]. Created between 1513 and 1516, it was to serve with another figure, the ''[[Rebellious Slave]]'', at the [[tomb of Pope Julius II]].<ref>Panofsky, Erwin. "The First Two Projects of Michelangelo's Tomb of Julius II". ''The Art Bulletin'', Volume 19, No. 4, December 1937. pp. 561–579.</ref> It is a [[marble]] figure 2.15 metres (7' 4") in height, and is held at the [[Musée du Louvre|Louvre]], Paris.
In 1976 the art historian Richard Fly wrote that it "suggests that moment when life capitulates before the relentless force of dead matter".<ref>Fly, Richard. ''Shakespeare's Mediated World''. Amherst, MA: [[University of Massachusetts Press]], 1976. p.30.</ref> However, in a recent scholarly volume entitled ''The Slave in European Art'', Charles Robertson discusses the ''Dying Slave'' in the context of real [[slavery]] in [[Italy]] during the time of the [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]].<ref>Charles Robertson, "Allegory and Ambiguity in Michelangelo's Slave", in ''The Slave in European Art: From Renaissance Trophy to Abolitionist Emblem'', ed. [[Elizabeth McGrath (art historian)|Elizabeth McGrath]] and Jean Michel Massing, London (The Warburg Institute) 2012.</ref>
Thirteen reproductions of the ''Dying Slave'' adorn the top storey of the [[12th arrondissement of Paris|12th arrondissement]] police station in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://breves-histoire.fr/vestiges/esclave-mourant-hotel-police/|title= « L’esclave mourant » de l’Hôtel de Police du 12ème|access-date=August 4, 2018| website=Brèves d'histoire|publisher=WordPress|language=French |trans-title=The Dying Slave on the police station of the 12th arrondissement}}</ref> Although [[Art Deco]] in style, the building was designed in 1991 by architects {{ill|Manuel Núñez Yanowsky|es}} and [[Miriam Teitelbaum]].<ref>[http://parisisinvisible.blogspot.com/2012/01/challenge-7-curious-figures-on-avenue.html Challenge 7: Curious figures on the Avenue Daumesnil] Retrieved 4 July 2018.</ref><ref>[http://www.paris-walking-tours.com/promenadeplantee.html Promenade Plantee] Retrieved 4 July 2018.</ref>
