The '''statue of Edward Snowden''', called '''''Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument 2.0''''' by its creators,<ref name="ANYApr15">{{cite news |url=http://animalnewyork.com/2015/theres-a-massive-illicit-bust-of-edward-snowden-stuck-to-a-war-monument-in-brooklyn/ |first1=Bucky |last1=Turco |title=There's a massive illicit bust of Edward Snowden stuck to a war monument in Brooklyn |publisher=Animal New York.com |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> was an [[Ephemerality|ephemeral]], illegally installed public [[statue]] of [[Edward Snowden]], an American [[whistleblower]] who [[news leak|leaked]] [[classified information]] from the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA) and was charged with [[federal crime]]s as a result.{{efn-ua|Snowden "leaked thousands of classified National Security Agency documents that exposed mass surveillance by the government" and was charged with violation of the [[Espionage Act]]. In 2013, he received asylum in Russia.<ref name=GuardApr15/>}} The [[bronze]]-like statue was placed in [[Fort Greene Park]] in [[Fort Greene, Brooklyn|Fort Greene]], [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], on April 6, 2015. It was attached to a [[Doric column]] on the perimeter of the park's [[Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument]],{{efn-ua|The Snowden sculpture was attached to an ancillary pillar—a smaller, peripheral Doric column on the corners of the Monument—and not to the central 149 feet (45 m) column that includes the crypt.}} a memorial and [[crypt]] which honors and inters the more than 11,500 American prisoners of war who died in the [[American Revolution]] while housed on British prison ships.<ref name="USAToday">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/04/06/edward-snowden-statue-illegally-placed-in-nyc-park/25371797/ |title=Edward Snowden statue illegally placed in NYC park |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015 |work=[[USA Today]] |first1=Yamiche |last1=Alcindor}}</ref><ref name="Mashable"/>{{efn-ua|The monument's dedication plaque estimates that 11,500 prisoners of war died in the prison ships, but others estimate the casualty count as high as 18,000.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Edwin G. Burrows |last=Burrows |first=Edwin G. |url=https://lihj.cc.stonybrook.edu/2012/articles/the-prisoners-of-new-york/ |title=The Prisoners of New York |journal=Long Island History Journal |year=2011 |volume=22 |number=2}}</ref>}}

Affixed atop an existing column, the statue was mounted by three anonymous artists and their helpers, who were dressed in white construction helmets and reflective vests in imitation of Parks Department workers,<ref name=nydn/> early in the morning of April 6, then covered and taken down by [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation|NYC Parks]] officials later that day.<ref name=GuardApr15>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-statue-bust-brooklyn-park-covered |first1=Alan |last1=Yuhas |title=Busted: Edward Snowden statue prompts cover-up at Brooklyn park |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/snowden-statue-in-new-york/article7076381.ece |title=Edward Snowden statue surfaces in NYC park |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=7 April 2015 |location=New York |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> A [[hologram]] tribute to Snowden was subsequently installed after the statue was removed.<ref name="NPR"/>

==Development and design==
The piece was conceived in 2014 by two artists from New York City and a sculptor from the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]]. The sculptor volunteered his time and skill in creating the statue, with the piece eventually costing thousands of dollars to create over six months.<ref name=ANYApr15/>{{efn-ua|"It's easily a 30 grand project... If it were bronze, it could be a $100,000 piece of artwork, maybe more."<ref name=ANYApr15/>}} The artwork consisted of a {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} high, {{Convert|100|lb|kg|adj = on}} bust of Snowden on top of a [[Doric column]], with a [[Plexiglas]] stand with Snowden's name on it.<ref name="GuardApr15"/><ref name="Yahoo">{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/photos/bust-of-edward-snowden-1428413495-slideshow/photo-provided-aymann-ismail-animalnewyork-monday-april-6-photo-001303800.html |title=Bust of Edward Snowden |publisher=[[Yahoo news]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref>

The piece was fused to [[Fort Greene Park]]'s [[Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument]]<ref name=GuardApr15/> in the pre-dawn hours of April 6, 2015.<ref name="USAToday"/> The sculptor recommended that the two artists create a bust after they had suggested a life-size statue of Snowden. The bust was made from [[Plaster#In art|Hydrocal]], a plaster-like substance resembling bronze in appearance, which was then fixed to the pre-existing column with a non-damaging adhesive.<ref name=ANYApr15/> The piece was designed to be similar in style to other sculptures in the park.{{efn-ua|Both design and color "expertly match[ed]" the existing motif and sculptures "from its bronze patina finish to Snowden's hair—which mimics the texture of the feather on the eagle."  The lettering for Snowden's name was "befitting of a monument."<ref name=ANYApr15/>}}

While it was very important to the artists that the piece be more than just a prop or [[papier-mache]] [[effigy]], they also wished not to damage the surface to which the bust would be bound. After some debate, they decided on an adhesive that would firmly hold the head in place, yet could be removed without marring the monument.<ref name=ANYApr15/> The statue had Snowden's name at its base, consistent with the names on the bases of other sculptures in the park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Edward-Snowden-Statue-Bust-New-York-NY-Brooklyn-War-Monument-298782461.html |title=Giant Edward Snowden Sculpture Appears on War Monument in Brooklyn Park |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref>

The ''Guardian'' newspaper expressed the view that the statue also looked like the former White House press secretary [[Jay Carney]] and some people thought it looked more like him than it did Snowden.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |title=Busted: Edward Snowden statue prompts cover-up at Brooklyn park |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/apr/06/edward-snowden-statue-bust-brooklyn-park-covered |accessdate=11 April 2015 |work=Guardian |date=6 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=newtekjournalismuk>{{cite news |title=Edward Snowden illicit bust removed |url=http://www.newtekjournalismukworld.com/eileen-kersey/edward-snowden-illicit-bust-removed |accessdate=11 April 2015 |work=New TEKJournalismUK |date=7 April 2015}}</ref>

''Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument 2.0'' is one of at least six sculptures and monuments to Snowden that have appeared around the world.{{efn-ua|Another such sculpture is the hologram that replaced this statue after its removal (see [[#Aftermath|"Aftermath" section]]).<ref name="untapped cities"/>}}  In October 2014, a statue of Snowden appeared in [[Union Square, Manhattan]], near [[Henry Kirke Brown]]'s [[Abraham Lincoln]] statue.<ref name="untapped cities"/> It was shown in conjunction with the [[Art in Odd Places]] festival and was sculpted by [[Jim Dessicino]], a [[Delaware]] artist.  One of the statue's observers compared Snowden to [[Daniel Ellsberg]], who leaked the ''[[Pentagon Papers]]'' to the ''[[New York Times]]''.{{efn-ua|Although the statue went unrecognized by most passersby, one opined: "He's our generation's Daniel Ellsberg ... What he did needed to be done."<ref name= "Jacobs">{{cite journal |title=There Is An Edward Snowden Statue In New York City, But Hardly Anyone Recognizes Him |first1=Harrison |last1=Jacobs |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/there-is-an-edward-snowden-statue-in-union-square-and-no-one-could-recognize-him-2014-10#ixzz3WpD4outF |journal=[[Business Insider]] |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref>}}

==Installation==
The creators of the statue, who were dubbed "[[guerrilla art]]ists" by some in the media,<ref name="Reuters">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN0MX16020150406 |title=Guerrilla artists leave Snowden statue in New York park |work=[[Reuters]] |first1=Laila |last1=Kearney |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name="TIME">{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3772906/edward-snowden-statue-removed/ |title=New York City Takes Down Edward Snowden Statue Erected By Guerrilla Artists |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015 |work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |first1=Alexandra |last1=Sifferlin}}</ref> released a statement to the Animal New York website detailing their motivations and documenting the statue's installation<ref name=ANYApr15/> in exchange for anonymity.{{efn-ua|"The artists, with the condition that they wouldn't be identified, allowed Animal New York to tag along and film the covert installation of what they call 'Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument 2.0.'"<ref name="Matthias">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/06/edward-snowden-statue-brooklyn-park-nypd_n_7011834.html |title=The NYPD Is Investigating This Giant Bust Of Edward Snowden Erected In A Brooklyn Park |newspaper=[[Huffington Post]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015 |first1=Christopher |last1=Matthias}}</ref>}} In their statement, the artists said:

{{quote|We have updated this monument to highlight those who sacrifice their safety in the fight against modern-day tyrannies. It would be a dishonor to those memorialized here to not laud those who protect the ideals they fought for, as Edward Snowden has by bringing the NSA's [[Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution|4th-Amendment]]-violating surveillance programs to light. All too often, figures who strive to uphold these ideals have been cast as criminals rather than in bronze...Our goal is to bring a renewed vitality to the space and prompt even more visitors to ponder the sacrifices made for their freedoms. We hope this inspires them to reflect upon the responsibility we all bear to ensure our liberties exist long into the future.<ref name="USAToday"/><ref name="RussiaToday">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=April 6, 2015 |title=Snowden cover-up: Unauthorized bust in Brooklyn becomes martyr to cause |url=http://rt.com/usa/247213-brooklyn-snowden-statue-installed-covered/ |newspaper=[[Russia Today]] |location=|access-date=April 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mai-Duc |first=Christine |date=April 6, 2015 |title=Edward Snowden statue appears in Brooklyn park, is quickly removed |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-edward-snowden-bust-brooklyn-park-20150406-htmlstory.html |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=|access-date=April 6, 2015}}</ref>}}

The artists also expressed their dismay with perceived public apathy at Snowden's revelations.<ref name=ANYApr15/>{{efn-ua|"It gives the whole thing so much more meaning," they told ''Mashable''. "It's not just about Snowden. It's about the ideals that he was trying to work towards and push others to care about."<ref name="RussiaToday"/>}}

While anticipating the sculpture's probable demise,{{efn-ua|"The artists are fully aware of the bust's inevitable destruction and have left themselves a few options, including one that involves deploying an army of mini-Snowden heads. 'We have a full size mold that can be poured again and its been 3D rendered, so we have the ability to print smaller ones at scale,' they said."<ref name=ANYApr15/>}} the creators told ''[[Mashable]]'' on April 6, 2015 that they "hope New York will embrace and protect this piece, much as when the ''[[Charging Bull|Wall Street Bull]]'' was granted a permanent public home after its guerrilla placement. Even though it's already on it's {{sic}} way towards being removed,{{efn-ua|The statue had been removed at 1:30 pm on April 6, 2015,<ref name="untapped cities"/> so the ''Mashable'' interview was probably conducted before then.}} the possibility exists for the city to make the piece available for public viewing in a sanctioned way."<ref name="Mashable">{{cite news |url=http://mashable.com/2015/04/06/snowden-sculpture-fort-greene-brooklyn/ |title=NYC officials remove Edward Snowden statue secretly installed in Brooklyn park |work=[[Mashable]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |first1=Brian |last1=Ries}}</ref>

The unsanctioned bust had appeared a few hours after [[HBO]]'s broadcast of [[John Oliver (comedian)|John Oliver]]'s ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Last Week Tonight]]'' interview with Snowden in Moscow.<ref name="TIME"/><ref name="Mail">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3028098/Bust-Edward-Snowden-sneaked-removed-NYC-park.html |title=Busted! Guerrilla artists sneak giant sculpture of Edward Snowden's head into Brooklyn park only to have it pulled down hours later by city workers |author1=[[Associated Press]] |author2=Daily Mail Reporter |date=6 April 2015 |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XEVlyP4_11M |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Government Surveillance (HBO) |date=April 5, 2015 |work=YouTube}}</ref>

==Removal and aftermath==
Some characterized the placement of Snowden's statue as an act of vandalism in support of a "traitor,"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-3029612/MAX-HASTINGS-Snowden-s-clearly-anarchist-traitor-endorse-just-dangerous.html |first1=Max |last1=Hastings |title=Snowden's clearly an anarchist and traitor. Those who endorse him are just as dangerous |date=7 April 2015 |newspaper=[[The Daily Mail]] |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> while others disagreed.{{efn-ua|"But while the dance of discord played out by the activist artists and park officials may have amused local spectators, it is representative of a divide within American society: the split between those who view Snowden as a national hero and those who believe he is a traitor."<ref name="Maza">{{cite news |title=Snowden statue points to divide in US society: Is he hero or traitor? (+video) |first1=Cristina |last1=Maza |date=7 April 2015 |newspaper=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/USA-Update/2015/0407/Snowden-statue-points-to-divide-in-US-society-Is-he-hero-or-traitor-video |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>
"'Vandalized?', some Fort Greene Focus readers asked, incredulously...  'Vandalized' awesomely, you mean,' joked reader Jeremy Friedman. 'I think it's in the same vein as [[Banksy]]—art not vandalism—and [[Pussy Riot]], protesting against a government,' said Ed Goldman, a resident and member of Fort Greene Peace. 'It seems to me that great art was usually not sanctioned by stakeholders and not considered appropriate, either in content, style or placement. Many of the great artists of the 19th and 20th century were considered practically heretics.'"<ref name="FortGreene">{{cite news |url=http://fortgreenefocus.com/blog/2015/04/07/art-protest-and-history-residents-react-to-snowden-bust-removal-from-prison-ship-martyrs-monument/ |title=Art, Protest, And History: Residents React To Snowden Bust's Removal From Prison Ship Martyrs Monument |newspaper= Fort Greene Focus |publisher= |first1=Heather |last1=Chin |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>}} The statue was up for only 12 to 13 hours before it was covered by blue [[tarpaulin]] and bound with rope at 12:30 pm on April 6, 2015, almost immediately after an official discovered it, then taken down an hour later.<ref name="untapped cities">{{cite web |first1=Michelle |last1=Young |url=http://untappedcities.com/2015/04/07/5-edward-snowden-statues-and-monuments-in-nyc-and-around-the-world/ |title=6 Edward Snowden Statues and Monuments in NYC and Around the World |publisher=Untapped Cities |date=April 8, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/mysterious-edward-snowden-statue-appears-in-brooklyn/ |title=Mysterious Edward Snowden statue appears in Brooklyn |publisher=[[CBS News]] |format=Video |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> Calling it an "art prank",<ref name="Maza"/> investigators from the [[New York City Police Department]]'s Intelligence Division reportedly gathered [[DNA]] and examining other evidence in an attempt to determine the identity of the artist or artists.<ref name="TIME"/><ref name="WNBCNewYork">{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Edward-Snowden-Statue-Bust-New-York-NY-Brooklyn-War-Monument-298782461.html |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015 |work=[[WNBC|NBC 4 News/WNBC]] |title=Giant Edward Snowden Sculpture Appears on War Monument in Brooklyn Park}}</ref> According to a spokesperson for the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]],  "[t]he erection of any unapproved structure or artwork in a city park is illegal."<ref name="USAToday"/><ref name="Matthias"/><ref name="Maza"/> Some passersby were annoyed at the covering of the statue, however.{{efn-ua|"Pedestrians... – a mix of dogwalkers, skateboarders, joggers and Fort Greene locals enjoying a day off – mostly expressed bemusement and irritation that the city had covered the column. One man wandered by to ask: 'When's the unveiling?'  A dogwalker ... said she thought the covering up ironic, considering Snowden's actions. 'I think he's actually upholding our values, what we believe in.' Others said they liked the art. 'It's all about exposure, right? They should uncover the tarp,' said Julia."<ref name=GuardApr15/>}}

The bust was being held at the NYPD's 88th [[Organization of the New York City Police Department|Precinct]] pending the investigation's outcome.<ref name="APFoxNews">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/04/06/bust-edward-snowden-sneaked-into-new-york-park-officials-remove-it-shortly/ |title=Bust of Edward Snowden sneaked into New York park; officials remove it shortly after arrival |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 8, 2015 |work=[[Associated Press|Fox News/Associated Press]]}}</ref>

Hours after the statue was removed, a group of New York artists calling themselves [[The Illuminator Art Collective]]—unrelated to the three artists who created the statue—used smoke and projection equipment to create an ephemeral "[[hologram]]" image of Snowden in place of the missing sculpture. This projection included Snowden's face above one of the pillars, as well as "Snowden" in white letters at the bottom of the pillar.<ref name="NPR"/> Collective artists said, "Our feeling is that while the State may remove any material artifacts that speak in defiance against incumbent authoritarianism, the acts of resistance remain in the public consciousness. And it is in sharing that act of defiance that hope resides."<ref name="MashableHologram">{{cite news |url=http://mashable.com/2015/04/07/edward-snowden-hologram-statue-brooklyn/ |work=[[Mashable]] |date=April 7, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |title=Hologram replaces Edward Snowden statue in Brooklyn park |first1=Brian |last1=Ries}}</ref>{{efn-ua|The Snowden Hologram was intended to maintain the message and express solidarity with the unknown artists "who installed the now-expunged statue."<ref name="Fishbein">{{cite web |url=http://gothamist.com/2015/04/07/edward_snowden_hologram.php#photo-1 |title=Illicit Edward Snowden Statue Replaced By Illicit Edward Snowden Hologram |first1=Rebecca |last1=Fishbein |first2=Kyle, Photographer |last2=Depew |newspaper=[[Gothamist]] |date=April 7, 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408184248/http://gothamist.com/2015/04/07/edward_snowden_hologram.php#photo-1 |archivedate=April 8, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}} The original artists said they were "touched" to see their bust and nameplate "reinstalled" with the use of light, adding that they were "surprised to see the way the statue was covered up before its removal, as though it were a profane statement."<ref name="NPR">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/04/07/398119206/an-edward-snowden-statue-was-replaced-by-another-snowden-image-last-night |title=An Edward Snowden Statue Was Replaced By A Hovering Snowden Image Last Night |first1=Sam |last1=Sanders |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref name="MashableHologram"/>

New York City has had a number of pieces of [[street art]], like the ''[[Charging Bull]]'', which have become [[cultural icon|cultural]] [[Secular icon|icons]] and tourist attractions.<ref name="Durante">{{cite book |first1=Dianne |last1=Durante |title=Outdoor Monuments of Manhattan: A Historical Guide |publisher=[[NYU Press]] |isbn=978-0-8147-1987-9 |pages=302 |date=February 2007}}</ref> It is uncertain whether this unsanctioned statue of Edward Snowden, considered just as valuable a work of art by some, will escape destruction.<ref name="Nosowitz">{{cite web |title=Wall Street's Bull Statue was once like Edward Snowden's Sculpture: Totally illegal |first1=Dan |last1=Nosowitz |date=7 April 2015 |url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/wall-street-s-charging-bull-statue-was-once-like-edward-snowden-s-bust-guerilla-art |newspaper=Atlas Obscura |publisher=atlasobscura.com |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> An online petition seeks the return of the statue to the Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument.<ref name="Azpiri">{{cite news |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1926679/artists-create-edward-snowden-hologram-after-statue-removed-from-brooklyn-park/ |location=Brooklyn |date=8 April 2015 |title=Artists create Edward Snowden hologram after statue removed from Brooklyn park |first1=Jon |last1=Azpiri |newspaper=[[Global News]] |accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>

The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' reported on April 14, 2015, that [[Ron Kuby]], a lawyer representing the unidentified artists, had asked [[New York City Police Commissioner]] [[Bill Bratton]] to return the statue to its creators.<ref name=nydn>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/artists-behind-edward-snowden-statue-nypd-return-article-1.2184732 |author=Chelsia Rose Marcius and Rich Schapiro |title=Artists behind Edward Snowden statue want NYPD to give it back |newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] |date=April 14, 2015 |accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> Kuby stated, "The statue itself is not contraband. Whatever the right of the Parks Department to remove an unauthorized sculpture, that does not translate into the right of the police to indefinitely detain a work of art."<ref name=nydn/> The artists planned to submit an application for authorized public display, and a Manhattan art gallery also expressed interest in exhibiting the Snowden sculpture.<ref name=nydn/>

==Return of sculpture==

After negotiations with the artists' attorney, the city returned the sculpture on May 6, 2015, assessing each artist a $50 fine for non-criminal trespassing due to their having illegally entered Fort Greene Park at night. Ron Kuby promised his clients' fines would be "promptly paid", and expressed gratitude that potential removal and storage fees for the sculpture were waived.<ref name=DailyNewsReturn>{{cite news |url=http://m.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/edward-snowden-bust-artists-recover-sculpture-city-article-1.2212650 |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 8, 2015 |title=Edward Snowden bust artists recover sculpture from the city |first=Dareh|last=Gregorian |work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref> A police summons identified the artists as Andrew Tider and Jeff Greenspan.<ref name=Wired>{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Greenberg |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/now-can-3-d-print-copy-nycs-illegal-snowden-bust/ |title=Now you can 3-D print your own copy of NYC's illegal Snowden bust |date=May 8, 2015 |accessdate=May 17, 2015 |work=''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''}}</ref>

The undamaged bust had its first post-police custody exhibition from May 8–17 at The Boiler in Brooklyn, in a show titled ''anonymity, no longer an option''.<ref name=MashableFree>{{cite news |url=http://mashable.com/2015/05/06/snowden-statue-free/ |title=Edward Snowden sculpture freed from NYPD custody |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 8, 2015 |first=Brian |last=Ries |work=[[Mashable]]}}</ref><ref name=Gothamist>{{cite news |title=Illicit Edward Snowden Bust Emerges From Protective Custody |url=http://gothamist.com/2015/05/06/snowden_busts_out.php |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 9, 2015 |work=[[Gothamist]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508233514/http://gothamist.com/2015/05/06/snowden_busts_out.php |archivedate=May 8, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The artists were reportedly applying to have the sculpture legally exhibited by New York City through the city's "Art in the Parks" program: "This time they're dotting their i's and crossing their t's," Kuby said.<ref name=DailyNewsReturn/><ref name=Gothamist/>

It was thereafter exhibited at the [[Brooklyn Museum]].<ref name="Cascone">{{cite news |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/edward-snowden-bust-brooklyn-museum-406727 |title=Exhibitions: Confiscated Edward Snowden Bust to Resurface at Brooklyn Museum |work=[[artnet]]|quote=A guerrilla artwork gets an institutional stamp of approval. |first1=Sarah |last1=Cascone |date=January 13, 2016 |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>

